### CSS Opacity & Transparency

**Opacity** controls how transparent an element is.

---

### The `opacity` Property

```css
div {
  opacity: 0.5; /* 0.0 (invisible) to 1.0 (fully visible) */
}
```

| Value | Effect |
|-------|--------|
| `1` | Fully opaque (default) |
| `0.8` | Slightly transparent |
| `0.5` | Half transparent |
| `0.2` | Very transparent |
| `0` | Fully invisible |

---

### Important: Children Inherit Opacity

When you set `opacity` on a parent, **all children** become transparent too.

```css
.parent {
  opacity: 0.5; /* Children also 50% transparent */
}
```

---

### Solution: Use RGBA/HSLA Instead

To make only the **background** transparent without affecting children:

```css
.parent {
  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5); /* Semi-transparent black */
  /* Children stay fully opaque */
}

/* Or with hex alpha */
.parent {
  background: #00000080;
}
```

---

### Hover Effects with Opacity

```css
img {
  opacity: 1;
  transition: opacity 0.3s;
}

img:hover {
  opacity: 0.7;
}
```

---

### Image Transparency

```css
img {
  opacity: 0.5;
  filter: alpha(opacity=50); /* IE8 and earlier */
}
```

---

### Text Transparency

```css
p {
  color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6); /* Text at 60% opacity */
}
```

> **Tip:** Use `rgba()` for backgrounds to avoid inheriting transparency to children. Use `opacity` when you want the whole element (including children) to fade.
